      "message": "\u003e In previous discord call, we discussed thinking these points:\n\u003e \n\u003e Moving from Bootstrap-vue to Bootstrap-vue-next would have minimal changes as compared to Bootstrap-vue to Bootstrap-5. Because most of the props of the components and classes are similar.\n\nIn my opinion, \"minimizing change\" isn\u0027t a design goal.  If we move to Bootstrap-vue-next, we very likely will have the same problem we\u0027ve had previously in the future, where the package goes unmaintained, and we are in the same boat again.\n\nDecoupling bootstrap from vue gives us complete control over what we do.\n\nWith that said, I\u0027m not going to put forward a lot of patches in this regard, and I\u0027m not a webui-vue maintainer, so if someone does the minimal Bootstrap-vue-next port, and the maintainers accept it, that\u0027s between the two of them.\n\nMy only goal in the vue3 port was to unfreeze something that seemed to have been stuck for years.\n\n\u003e \n\u003e After removing compat mode, we might still require some changes or fixes. So, Merging to master after removing compat mode and done with the fixes is a safer approach.\n\u003e \n\u003e Any thoughts?\n\nI don\u0027t really want to rely on \"might require some changes\" for making major refactoring decisions.  If things require changes, make the changes and submit them to review.  If we cause bugs, fix them or revert the patches that cause the bugs.  All of those things can happen on master, with the maintainers we have.\n\nGoing down the path of removing compat mode in the vue3 branch bifurcates the community testing, and delays integration, which is a far more dangerous problem than possibly injecting a minor bug or two in code that we\u0027ve tested properly.",
